Filter Data

According to the edgeR protocol, weakly expressed and non-informative features should be removed. Therefore, our next step involves filtering out genes that have low counts. It is recommended in edgeR to remove genes that have less than one read per million (CPM) in n of the samples, where n is the size of the smallest group of replicates. For my dataset, there are 5 samples in each group (miR-155 and negative control), so we set n=5.

# The duplicate issues have been largely solved

Normalization

To choose a suitable normalization method, the first step is to obtain the distribution of the data using a box plot and a density plot.

We obtained some warnings from R console complaining that outliers (-Inf) are not drawn in our box plot. After an examination of the dataframe log2Cpms, I found that an outlier is obtained when the genes CPM=0 for that sample. Since our criteria is to remove genes without at least 1 read per million in 5 of the samples and weve removed those genes, we can ignore the warnings and move on to the next step.

Next, well make a density plot for the log2-CPMs.

drawDensityPlot <- function(countsData, title, cex) {
  # Calculate the density in each sample
  countsDensity <- apply(log2(edgeR::cpm(countsData)), 2, density)
  
  # Calculate the limits across all the samples
  xlim <- 0
  ylim <- 0
  for (i in 1:length(countsDensity)) {
    xlim <- range(c(xlim, countsDensity[[i]]$x))
    ylim <- range(c(ylim, countsDensity[[i]]$y))
  }
  
  # Set the colors and line types for the density plot
  cols <- rainbow(length(countsDensity))
  ltys <- rep(1, length(countsDensity))
  
  # Initialize the plot
  plot(countsDensity[[1]], xlim = xlim, ylim = ylim, type = "n",
       ylab = "Smoothing density of log2-CPM",
       main = title, cex.lab = 0.85)
  
  # Plot each line
  for (i in 1:length(countsDensity)) {
    lines(countsDensity[[i]], col = cols[i], lty = ltys[i])
  }
  
  # Create a legend
  legend("topright", colnames(log2Cpms), col = cols, lty = ltys,
         cex = cex, merge = TRUE)
}
countsData <- expDataFiltered[, 3:12]
drawDensityPlot(countsData, 
                title = "Density Plot of log2-CPM for miR-155 RNASeq Samples",
                cex = 0.75)

The distribution of the samples are not normal. We need to apply a normalization method to account for some of the technical variations in our data. The authors in the original paper used the DESeq2 package for their counts normalization. Since edgeR and DESeq2 are both based on the hypothesis that most genes are not differentially expressed and they give very similar results (add), I decided to use the edger package for my data normalization. I want to compare the results with the authors to see if theres anything different.

Exploratory Data Analysis

Lets compare the box plot and density plot before and after normalization to demonstrate the effect of normalization on our data.

# Compare the box plots
par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
drawBoxPlot(log2Cpms, title = "Original Counts")
drawBoxPlot(log2(normalizedCounts), title = "Normalized")

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))

countsData <- expDataFiltered[, 3:12]
drawDensityPlot(countsData, title = "Original Counts", cex = 0.4)
drawDensityPlot(normalizedCounts, title = "Normalized", cex = 0.4)

Even though the density plots almost look the same before and after normalization, we do see the effect of normalization through the comparison of the box plots: the medians of each sample are adjusted and now fit the median line better. For both box and density plots, the post-normalization plot distributes in the same intervals with the same density center as the pre-normalization plot, suggesting correct use of normalization in this case.

Well also use a multidimensional scaling (MDS) plot to represent the distances between samples post normalization.

limma::plotMDS(d, labels = rownames(samples), col = c("darkgreen", "blue")[factor(samples$cell_type)])

Notice that the two groups of the samples are clearly separated, suggesting that miR-155 groups and negative control groups indeed have different behaviors across their counts and differential expressions.

Next, well use edgeR to calculate the dispersion, which measures how much variation there is in our samples.

# Calculate the dispersion
modelMatrix <- model.matrix(~samples$donors + samples$cell_type+0)
dispersion <- edgeR::estimateDisp(d, modelMatrix)

# Plot the biological coefficient of variation (BCV)
edgeR::plotBCV(dispersion, col.tagwise = "black", col.common = "red")


# Plot the mean-variance relationship
edgeR::plotMeanVar(dispersion, 
                   show.raw.vars = TRUE,

Identifier Mapping

In this final step, well map the ensembl gene IDs to HGNC symbols in our dataset.

# Load the biomaRt library and choose the Mart and Dataset to use
library(biomaRt)

# The line below is run to avoid Error in curl::curl_fetch_memory(url, handle = handle)
# when running the useMart function
httr::set_config(httr::config(ssl_verifypeer = 0L))
ensembl <- useMart("ensembl")
hsapiens <- useDataset("hsapiens_gene_ensembl", mart = ensembl)

# Before the conversion, we'll remove the version numbers after "." in the 
# ensembl gene ID column in our original dataset for use in biomaRt
newExpDataFiltered <- expDataFiltered
newExpDataFiltered$GeneID <- gsub("\\..*", "", newExpDataFiltered$GeneID)

# Convert the ensembl gene IDs to HGNC symbols
conversions <- getBM(attributes = c("ensembl_gene_id", "hgnc_symbol"),
                     filters = c("ensembl_gene_id"),
                     values = newExpDataFiltered$GeneID,
                     mart = hsapiens)

We see that merging the two datasets resulted in a total of 13004 rows, but there are only 13003 unique Ensembl gene IDs. This means that two rows have the same Ensembl gene ID. Lets find out which rows those are.

It only resulted in one row, which means that there is only one row containing the Ensembl ID ENSG00000276085 in the original dataset.

Now is a good idea to do a manual verification for the two HGNC symbols: CCL3L3 and CCL3L1. CCL3L3 has ID ENSG00000276085.1, while CCL3L1 has ID ENSG00000277336.2. It seems like there might be a slight problem with mapping the gene symbols, possibly an Ensembl version update issue.

We have ENSG00000276085.1 in our original dataset, so Ive decided to remove the row containing CCL3L1 from the normalizedCountsHGNC.

# Remove the row containing CCL3L1 from normalizedCountsHGNC
normalizedCountsHGNC <- normalizedCountsHGNC[-c(12596), ]

Interpretation

  1. What are the control and test conditions of the dataset?

The test condition is CD14+ monocytes transfected with miR-155. The control condition is CD14+ monocytes transfected with negative control mimic.

  1. Why is the dataset of interest to you?

Im fascinated by the disease mechanisms of autoimmune diseases - your immune system attacks healthy cells by mistake and causes inflammation. And this dataset studies the role of miR-155 that is implicated in rheumatoid arthritis (RA, an autoimmune disease), which is a very painful disease that causes many inconveniences and can damage other body systems.

  1. Were there expression values that were not unique for specific genes? How did you handle these?

All expression values and Ensembl IDs were unique for specific genes in the original dataset.

  1. Were there expression values that could not be mapped to current HUGO symbols?

There were a total of 25 out of 13003 (~0.1%) genes that could not be mapped to current HUGO symbols. Since these genes only make up a small amount of the dataset, I left them as NAs and will work with the Ensembl ID to find the gene if needed in future analyses.

  1. How many outliers were removed?

No significant outliers were found so none were removed.

  1. How did you handle replicates?

The samples came from 5 different donors, which are noise sources. To handle replicates, I first extracted the donors and cell types from the original dataset to get a clear picture of what the samples are. Then, I applied normalization to take care of technical variations. Finally, genes with low counts in more than 5 samples removed to ensure the quality of the data.

  1. What is the final coverage of your dataset?

The final coverage of my dataset is 13003 genes with their Ensembl gene IDs, HGNC symbols, and normalized counts in 10 samples.
